== Occurrence ==
The occurrence of bohrium in nature in such minerals as [[molybdenite]], through long-lived isotopes. However this has been deemed as highly unlikely.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last1=Ivanov|first1=A. V.|title=The possible existence of Hs in nature from a geochemical point of view|journal=Physics of Particles and Nuclei Letters|volume=3|pages=165|year=2006|doi=10.1134/S1547477106030046|issue=3|arxiv = nucl-th/0604052 |bibcode = 2006PPNL....3..165I }}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Isotopes==
{{main|Isotopes of bohrium}}
A total of eleven isotopes of bohrium have been characterized. The proton-rich isotopes with masses 260, 261, and 262 were directly produced by cold fusion, those with mass 262 and 264 were reported in the chains of the elements 109 and 111, while the neutron-rich isotopes with masses 266, 267 were created in irradiations of actinide targets. The four most neutron-rich ones with masses 270, 271, 272, and 274 appear in decay chains of &lt;sup&gt;282&lt;/sup&gt;113, &lt;sup&gt;287&lt;/sup&gt;115, &lt;sup&gt;288&lt;/sup&gt;115, and &lt;sup&gt;294&lt;/sup&gt;117 respectively. These ten isotopes have half-lives ranging from 8 miliseconds to 0.9 minute, and all undergo alpha-decay.&lt;ref name=&quot;Doi_&quot; /&gt;

