  <page>
    <title>Bay of Quinte</title>
    <id>4204</id>
    <revision>
      <id>418639015</id>
      <timestamp>2011-03-13T17:26:02Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Yobot</username>
        <id>7328338</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>/* Quinte Region */[[WP:CHECKWIKI]] error 61 fixes + [[WP:GENFIXES|general fixes]], References after punctuation per [[WP:REFPUNC]] and [[WP:PAIC]] using [[Project:AWB|AWB]] (7579)</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Location map | Ontario
 |label=Bay of Quinte
 |alt=Bay of Quinte is located between Toronto and Ottawa, Ontario, Canada
 |lat= 44.16
 |long=-77.15
 |caption=Location within Ontario}}
[[File:Indian Point PEC.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Indian Point, western-most point of [[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]] and entrance to the Bay of Quinte.]]
The '''Bay of Quinte''' ({{IPA-en|ˈkwɪnti|pron}}) is a long, thin bay shaped like the letter &quot;Z&quot; on the northern shore of [[Lake Ontario]] in the province of [[Ontario]], Canada. It is close to the mouth of the [[Saint Lawrence River]] that connects the [[Great Lakes]] to the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]]. It is located about 200 kilometers east of [[Toronto]] and 400 west of [[Montreal]].

The name &quot;Quinte&quot; is derived from &quot;''Kente''&quot;, which was the name of an early French Catholic [[Mission (Christian)|mission]] located on the south shore of what is now [[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.greatcanadianlakes.com/ontario/lake_ontario/cul_page3.htm Great Canadian Lakes, Lake Ontario - Saving Souls in Kente] Retrieved: 2010-04-15&lt;/ref&gt;  

The Bay, as it is known locally, provides some of the best trophy [[Walleye]] angling in North America as well as most sport fish common to the great lakes.  The bay is subject to [[algae bloom]]s in late summer which are a naturally occurring phenomenon and do not indicate pollution other than from agricultural runoff.  [[Zebra mussel]]s as well as the other invasive species found in the great lakes are present.

The Quinte area played a vital role to bootleggers during [[Prohibition in the United States]], with large volumes of booze being produced in the area, and shipped via boat on the Bay to [[Lake Ontario]] finally arriving in New York State where it was distributed.  Illegal sales of liquor accounted for many fortunes in and around [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]].

Tourism in the area is significant, especially in the summer months due to the Bay of Quinte and its fishing, local golf courses, provincial parks, and wineries.

==Geography==
[[File:BayofQuinteMap-1108.JPG|thumb|left|240px|Map of the Bay of Quinte Area]]
The northern side of the bay is defined by Ontario's mainland, while the southern side follows the shore of the Prince Edward County headland. Beginning in the east with the outlet to Lake Ontario, the bay runs west-southwest for {{km to mi|25}} to [[Picton, Ontario|Picton]] (although this section is also called Adolphus Reach), where it turns north-northwest for another {{km to mi|20}} as far as [[Deseronto, Ontario|Deseronto]]. From there it turns south-southwest again for another {{km to mi|40}}, running past [[Big Island (Bay of Quinte)|Big Island]] on the south and [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]] on the north. The width of the bay rarely exceeds two kilometers. The bay ends at [[Trenton, Ontario|Trenton]] ([[Quinte West, Ontario|Quinte West]]) and the [[Trent River (Ontario)|Trent River]], both also on the north side. The [[Murray Canal]] has been cut through the few miles separating the end of the bay and Lake Ontario on the west side. The Trent River is part of the [[Trent-Severn Waterway]], a canal connecting Lake Ontario to [[Lake Simcoe]] and then [[Georgian Bay]] on [[Lake Huron]].

There are several sub-bays off the Bay of Quinte, including Hay Bay, Big Bay, and Muscote Bay.

==Quinte Region==
'''Quinte''' is also a region comprising several communities situated along the Bay of Quinte, including [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]] which is the largest city in the Quinte Region, and represents a mid-point between [[Montreal]], [[Ottawa]], and [[Toronto]].

The Greater Bay of Quinte area includes the municipalities of Brighton, Quinte West, Belleville, Prince Edward County, and Greater Napanee as well as the Native Mohawk Territory of Tyendinaga.  Overall population of the area exceeds 200,000.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.quintedevelopment.com/v2/assets/File/Population%202006.pdf Demographics of the greater Bay of Quinte region] Retrieved: 2010-04-19&lt;/ref&gt;

===Communities===
* [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]]
* [[Quinte West, Ontario|Quinte West]] (Including [[Trenton, Ontario|Trenton]], the Village of [[Frankford, Ontario|Frankford]], Murray Township and [[Sidney Township]])
*[[Brighton, Ontario|Brighton]]
* [[Shannonville, Ontario|Shannonville]]
