* [[Natasha Gregson Wagner]] as Cassandra
* [[Thomas Jane|Tom Jane]] as Zeph
* [[Candy Clark]] as Mrs. Summers
* [[Randall Batinkoff]] as Jeffrey
* [[Ben Affleck]] (''uncredited'') as Basketball Player #10
* [[Ricki Lake]] (''uncredited'') as Charlotte

==Canon status==
Many of the details given in the film differ from the [[Buffyverse canon|continuity]] of the later television series. For example, Buffy's history is dissimilar, and both the vampires' and [[Slayer (Buffy the Vampire Slayer)|Slayer]]'s abilities are depicted differently. Joss Whedon has expressed his disapproval with the movie's interpretation of the script,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.cise.ufl.edu/cgi-bin/cgiwrap/hsiao/buffy/get-archive?date=19990117 Bronze VIP Archive - January 17, 1999&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; stating, &quot;I finally sat down and had written it and somebody had made it into a movie, and I felt like &amp;mdash; well, that's not quite her. It's a start, but it's not quite the girl.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;Ervin-Gore, Shawna, &quot;[http://www.darkhorse.com/news/interviews.php?id=737 Dark Horse; Joss Whedon]&quot; ''darkhorse.com'' (2001).&lt;/ref&gt;

According to the ''Official Buffy Watcher's Guide'', Whedon wrote the pilot to the TV series as a sequel to his ''original'' script, which is why the show makes references to things that didn't happen in the movie. In 1999 [[Dark Horse Comics]] released a graphic novel adaptation of Whedon's original script under the title, ''[[The Origin (Buffy comic)|The Origin]]''. Whedon stated: &quot;The ''Origin'' comic, though I have issues with it, CAN pretty much be accepted as canonical. They did a cool job of combining the movie script with the series, that was nice, and using the series Merrick and  not a certain OTHER thespian who shall remain hated.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cise.ufl.edu/cgi-bin/cgiwrap/hsiao/buffy/get-archive?date=19990117 |title=Bronze VIP Archive - January 17, 1999 |publisher=Cise.ufl.edu |date=1999-01-17 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Box office==
The movie debuted at number 5 at the box office.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office `Honors' Tops in a Lackluster Bunch|publisher= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1994-05-10/entertainment/ca-56005_1_weekend-box-office|accessdate=2010-12-28}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Home releases==
The film was released on [[VHS]] in the U.S. in 1992 from [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment|Fox Video]] and re-released in 1995 under the &quot;Twentieth Century Fox Selections&quot; banner from [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]]. It was released on [[DVD]] in the US in 2001.

